# {{lb|en|typography}} The [[punctuation]] [[mark]] ⟨'''<big><big><big>[[,]]</big></big></big>'''⟩ [[use]]d to [[indicate]] a [[set off]] [[part]]s of a [[sentence]] or between [[element]]s of a [[list]].
#* '''1828''', Richard Thomson, [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=IyUNAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover ''Illustrations of the History of Great Britain'', Vol. II], [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=IyUNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA145 pp. 145–6]:
#*: No points were used by the ancient printers, excepting the [[colon]] and the [[period]]; but, after some time, a short [[oblique stroke]], called a [[virgil]], was introduced, which answered to the modern [[comma]]. In the fifteenth century this punctuation was improved by the famous Aldus Manutius with the typographical art in general; when he gave a better shape to the [[comma]], added the [[semicolon]], and assigned to the former points more proper places.
# {{lb|en|Romanian|_|typography}} A [[similar]]-[[looking]] [[subscript]] [[diacritical mark]].
# A European and North American [[butterfly]], {{taxlink|Polygonia c-album|species|noshow=1|ver=161201}}, of the family [[Nymphalidae]].
# {{lb|en|music}} a difference in the calculation of nearly identical [[interval]]s by different ways.
# {{lb|en|genetics}} A [[delimit]]ing [[marker]] between items in a [[genetic]] [[sequence]].
# In [[Ancient Greek]] [[rhetoric]], a short clause, something less than a colon, originally denoted by comma marks. In antiquity it was defined as a combination of words having no more than eight syllables in all. It was later applied to longer phrases, e.g. the {{w|Johannine comma}}.
